flowchart LR

  subgraph INTENT["1. Path objective"]
    G1["Turn an external engine-owned world into a governed, platform-usable source-of-stream basis"]
    G2["Preserve the producer/platform ownership boundary while still materializing platform-readable source surfaces"]
    G3["Realize the source basis through a production-patterned route rather than a local shortcut"]
  end

  subgraph ENTRY["2. Entry basis"]
    E1["A declared external oracle source exists"]
    E2["Source namespace and oracle engine run id are pinned under the oracle-store boundary"]
    E3["A raw input prefix is declared and readable"]
    E4["Managed stream-sort handles resolve before closure can be attempted"]
    E5["The active posture is repinned to external_raw_upload_then_managed_sort"]
    E6["The canonical bucket is fraud-platform-dev-full-object-store, not a legacy dev-min copy mirror"]
  end

  subgraph SPINE["5. Broad route logic"]
    R1["External oracle world"]
    R2["Raw upload into the oracle-store input boundary"]
    R3["Managed distributed sort"]
    R4["Realized source surfaces with receipts, manifests, and parity"]
    R5["Canonical oracle basis for platform use"]
  end

  subgraph CARRIES["4. What the path carries"]
    C1["Source identity:<br/>oracle source namespace + oracle engine run id"]
    C2["Sealed-world identity model:<br/>manifest_fingerprint, parameter_hash, seed, scenario_id, run_id"]
    C3["Source materialization inputs:<br/>raw uploaded oracle files under the oracle input prefix"]
    C4["Realization outputs and proofs:<br/>stream_view surfaces, manifests, stream-sort receipts, parity reports, required-output matrices"]
    C5["The handles registry pins the active required-output set and sort-key map"]
    C6["The data-engine interface pins the identity and immutability rules the path must preserve"]
  end

  subgraph LOGIC["6. Logical design reading"]
    L1["The platform treats the engine world as producer-owned external truth"]
    L2["The platform then creates a platform-readable realization layer from that world"]
    L3["This prevents the platform from pretending it owns the oracle world"]
    L4["It also prevents the platform from consuming source data through informal local transformations"]
    L5["Oracle Store is warm source-of-stream zone in S3: producer write-owned, platform read-only"]
  end

  subgraph SEATING["7. Concrete seating in the current wired system"]
    S1["Oracle boundary in S3 under oracle-store/{oracle_source_namespace}/{oracle_engine_run_id}/input/"]
    S2["The canonical bucket and input prefix are explicitly repinned in the notes"]
    S3["The realization step is seated in the managed sort lane"]
    S4["The active contract requires managed sort and forbids local sort for the dev_full runtime path"]
    S5["Concrete realized outputs:<br/>stream_view/ts_utc/output_id=<output_id>/"]
    S6["Current wired realization also includes later truth_view/ts_utc/output_id=<output_id>/ preparation"]
    S7["Run-process closure artifacts include oracle readiness snapshot and required-output matrix"]
  end

  subgraph RATIONALE["8. Why the design looks like this"]
    Y1["The design preserves the oracle ownership boundary: producer write-owned, platform read-only"]
    Y2["It removes legacy copy-based ambiguity that would blur what is canonical versus a convenience mirror"]
    Y3["It aligns with production-pattern law and the no-laptop-runtime posture"]
    Y4["That is why local sort is forbidden and managed sort is required"]
    Y5["The oracle gate fails closed on receipts and parity instead of accepting 'looks readable' as enough"]
    Y6["These are architecture reasons, not performance excuses"]
  end

  subgraph CONTRACT["9. External contract pressure"]
    X1["The data-engine interface pins world identity by partition tokens and immutable outputs for a fixed identity"]
    X2["It distinguishes traffic from join surfaces, truth products, audit evidence, and ops telemetry"]
    X3["No PASS -> no read"]
    X4["Platform components must verify segment gates before treating gated outputs as authoritative"]
    X5["Traffic stays thin, joins happen inside the platform, and no future-leaking surfaces may be used for RTDL"]
    X6["So this path must produce the exact source surfaces the platform will later honor under those semantic rules"]
  end

  subgraph TRADEOFFS["10. Trade-offs and constraints"]
    T1["This path deliberately chooses discipline over convenience"]
    T2["It is slower and more ceremony-heavy than ad hoc local copy or local sort"]
    T3["Closure requires raw upload receipt, managed sort receipt, manifest readability, required-output checks, and parity checks"]
    T4["The cost buys ownership clarity, source legitimacy, materialization legitimacy, replay and audit confidence, and production-pattern alignment"]
    T5["Managed sort friction surfaced honestly: scheduler capacity issues, driver materialization timeouts, and later IAM/KMS permission issues"]
    T6["Those issues were handled at the IaC/runtime level rather than bypassed with manual shortcuts"]
  end

  subgraph NECESSITY["11. Necessity test"]
    N1["Without this path, the platform can still be described, but its source basis becomes muddy"]
    N2["The platform loses a governed way to turn external engine truth into platform-usable source surfaces"]
    N3["The producer/platform ownership boundary becomes easy to violate"]
    N4["stream_view materialization loses legitimacy"]
    N5["Parity and manifest proof disappear"]
    N6["Later runtime joins and learning surfaces rest on a weaker foundation"]
    N7["That directly weakens A"]
  end

  subgraph CLOSURE["3. Owned outcome and 12. What this path proves for A"]
    O1["raw upload receipt"]
    O2["managed stream-sort receipt"]
    O3["required outputs present"]
    O4["stream_view materialization checks passed"]
    O5["manifest and contract checks passed"]
    O6["canonical external source binding instead of an ad hoc duplicated copy"]
    O7["Owned outcome: canonical oracle basis with usable realized stream_view surfaces and proof they are trustworthy"]
    O8["truth_view is part of the current wired realization story, but the primary closure anchor here is canonical oracle basis plus valid stream_view realization"]
    A1["Purpose claim:<br/>the platform has a specific job for realizing the external source world"]
    A2["Intentionality claim:<br/>the route is explicitly external raw upload -> managed sort -> realized source surfaces"]
    A3["Materialization claim:<br/>the path is concretely seated in S3 oracle-store prefixes, managed sort runtime, and durable materialization/evidence outputs"]
    A4["Contract claim:<br/>the path preserves producer/platform ownership boundaries and the engine's identity, immutability, and gate laws"]
    A5["Constraint-awareness claim:<br/>copy-based ambiguity, local-sort convenience, and unmanaged shortcuts were explicitly rejected"]
    A6["Quantified closure claim:<br/>11,465 files and 92,622,942,077 bytes in the repinned full-tree upload;<br/>later stream_view parity evidence recorded for four required outputs with exact row parity matches"]
    A7["A-level meaning:<br/>the external engine world becomes a governed, materially realized, semantically constrained source basis instead of an informal file backdrop"]
  end

